PROJECT TITLE: SUPER-ELASTIC COPPER BASED MEMORY ALLOYS & ENGINEERED CEMENTITIOUS COMPOSITES FOR SEISMIC RESILIENCY :::: PROJECT DESCRIPTION: DISPLACEMENT CAPACITY AND ENERGY DISSIPATION IN CONVENTIONAL RC COLUMNS COMES AT THE COST OF SEVERE DAMAGE TO CONCRETE, STEEL, AND PERMANENT DISPLACEMENT OF BRIDGES AND OTHER STRUCTURES INCLUDING MARINE STRUCTURES DURING EXTREME EVENT. EVENTS SUCH AS EARTHQUAKE, ICE LOAD, COLLISION BY VESSELS AND VEHICLES, TSUNAMIS, CHECK FLOODS, AND BLASTS. THE RESILIENCY OF THESE STRUCTURES CAN BE SIGNIFICANTLY INCREASED IF PROBLEMS CAN BE ELIMINATED USING SHAPE MEMORY ALLOY (SMA) AND ENGINEERED CEMENTITIOUS COMPOSITE (ECC). COMPARISON OF RESIDUAL DISPLACEMENT IN LAB TESTING OF COLUMN MODELS DEMONSTRATED THAT RESIDUAL DISPLACEMENT WAS 86% LOWER THAN THE COLUMNS WITH CONVENTIONAL MATERIALS. THE WASHINGTON STATE DEPARTMENT OF TRANSPORTATION (WSDOT) IMPLEMENTED SMA/ECC IN THE COLUMNS OF THE SR-99 ON-RAMP BRIDGE IN DOWNTOWN SEATTLE. WITH THE PRICE OF NICKEL-TITANIUM SMA (NITI) BEING 90 TIMES THE MILD STEEL COST, BRIDGE OWNERS MAY BE RELUCTANT TO ADOPT THE MATERIAL. TO OFFSET SMA MATERIAL COSTS, A NEW GENERATION OF COPPER-ALUMINUM-MANGANESE (CAM) SMA BAR THATÂ€™S APPROXIMATELY 80-90% LESS EXPENSIVE THAN NITI IS EMERGING. THE ALLOY IS COMPOSED OF 72% COPPER, 17% ALUMINUM, AND 11% MANGANESE. NO. 10 CAM BARS HAVE BEEN DEVELOPED AND RECENTLY TESTED ALONG WITH HEADED REINFORCEMENT CORPÂ€™S (HRC) COUPLERS AT UNIVERSITY OF NEVADAÂ€“RENO (UNR) WITH GOOD RESULTS, I.E. LARGE-DIAMETER BARS FOR USE IN ACTUAL BRIDGES HAVE ALREADY PROVEN TO BE FEASIBLE. CAM BARS ARE CONNECTED TO STEEL BARS THAT EXTEND INTO COLUMNS, FOOTINGS, OR CAP BEAMS. CAM-REINFORCED COLUMNS INCORPORATING THE (HRC) SPLICE HAVE NOT BEEN STUDIED, BUT AN EXPLORATORY STUDY WAS CONDUCTED BY SHAKE TABLE TESTING OF A COLUMN MODEL INCORPORATING THREADED CAM BARS. THESE BARS HAD TO BE MACHINED TO A DOG BONE SHAPE TO AVOID FRACTURE AT THREADED ENDS. ENGINEERED CEMENTITIOUS COMPOSITE (ECC) WAS USED IN THE PLASTIC HINGE REGION. ECC IS A FIBER-REINFORCED CEMENT-BASED CONCRETE WHICH HAS HIGH TENSILE DUCTILITY.

PROJECT TITLE: AN INNOVATIVE INTERNET OF THINGS (IOT) TECHNOLOGY FOR COMPREHENSIVE TRAFFIC  SENSING AND V2X APPLICATIONS :::: PROJECT DESCRIPTION: THIS WASHINGTON STATE TRANSPORTATION INNOVATION COUNCIL FUNDED PROJECT (PROJECT TEAM INCLUDES WSDOT, THE CITIES OF BELLEVUE AND LYNNWOOD, AND THE UW STAR LAB) PROPOSES TO INSTALL AND IMPLEMENT MOBILE UNIT FOR SENSING TRAFFIC (MUST) SENSORS, DEVELOPED AT THE UW STAR LAB, ALONG ROADWAYS FOR DATA COLLECTION, CONDITION ASSESSMENT, AND V2X APPLICATIONS. THE GOAL OF THE PROJECT IS TO DEPLOY THESE SENSORS ALONG ROADWAYS WITH HIGH CRASH RISKS, SUCH AS SEGMENTS WITH HORIZONTAL AND/OR VERTICAL CURVES, AND AT LOCATIONS WITH FREQUENT SNOW OR ICE COVERAGE, ETC. THESE SENSORS WILL THEN BE USED TO MONITOR TRAFFIC AND ROADWAY SURFACE AND ENVIRONMENTAL CONDITIONS, COMMUNICATE WITH TRAFFIC OPERATIONS CENTERS, AND BROADCAST USEFUL INFORMATION TO ROAD USERS WHEN NEEDED.  REAL-TIME COLLECTION OF TRAFFIC DATA, ROADWAY SURFACE CONDITIONS, AND ENVIRONMENTAL CONDITIONS, AND THE EFFICIENT BROADCASTING OF THIS INFORMATION TO ROAD USERS, CAN SIGNIFICANTLY IMPROVE ROADWAY SAFETY CONDITIONS, AND IS ONE OF THE MOST IMPORTANT OPERATIONAL GOALS FOR ITS. SPECIFICALLY, THIS PROJECT WILL UTILIZE SENSORS TO COLLECT TRAFFIC DATA (VOLUME, SPEED, VEHICLE TYPES, ETC.), ROADWAY SURFACE CONDITIONS (SNOW, ICE, RAIN, ETC.), AND WEATHER CONDITIONS (TEMPERATURE, HUMIDITY, VISIBILITY, ETC.). IT WILL INVESTIGATE THE MOST COST-EFFECTIVE WAY FOR THE SENSORS TO TRANSMIT USEFUL DATA TO THE TRANSPORTATION AGENCIES AND COMMUNICATE WITH THE OPERATIONS CENTERS, AS WELL AS BROADCAST REAL-TIME INFORMATION TO ROAD USERS THROUGH VARIOUS CHANNELS (E.G., OUR CUSTOMIZED MOBILE APP, VARIABLE MESSAGE SIGNS, RADIO BROADCAST). IN ADDITION, THE TEAM WILL SUMMARIZE PROJECT FINDINGS INTO AN APPLICATION GUIDEBOOK THAT CAN BE USED TO TRAIN STATE AND LOCAL AGENCIES TO IMPLEMENT THIS TECHNOLOGY AND ALSO SHARE THE FINDINGS AT CONFERENCES AND IN WEBINARS.

PROJECT TITLE: UNDERWATER RADIATED VESSEL NOISE STUDY :::: PROJECT DESCRIPTION: COLLECTION OF NEW UNDERWATER VESSEL NOISE DATA BY VESSEL CLASS FOLLOWING ANSI STANDARDS.  THE CONSULTANT IN COORDINATION WITH WSF WOULD DEPLOY AUTONOMOUS HYDROPHONES AT UP TO 5 FERRY TERMINALS (PORT TOWNSEND/COUPEVILLE, FRIDAY HARBOR, ANACORTES, MUKILTEO/CLINTON, EDMONDS/KINGSTON) TO COLLECT VESSEL NOISE AS IT PASSES AT FULL OPERATIONAL SPEED.  CONCURRENT SOUND/VIBRATION MEASUREMENTS WILL BE COLLECTED FOR SPECIFIC MECHANICAL EQUIPMENT LOCATED INSIDE THE VESSEL(S) USING ACOUSTIC AND/OR VIBRATION SENSORS TO EVALUATE STRUCTURE BORNE NOISE LEVELS AND SEA CONNECTED SYSTEMS .  DETERMINING THE PEAK RMS AND CUMULATIVE SOUND EXPOSURE LEVEL (CSEL) UNDERWATER SOURCE NOISE LEVELS CAN BE DONE BY USING THE AUTOMATIC IDENTIFICATION SYSTEM (AIS) SHIP-TRAFFIC DATA TO DETERMINE ACCURATE DISTANCES TO THE VESSEL AS IT PASSED BY THE HYDROPHONE AND THEN BACK CALCULATE THE SOUND LEVEL TO 1 METER FROM THE SOURCE. THE ANALYSIS WILL INCORPORATE THE WEIGHTING FUNCTIONS ASSOCIATED WITH THE FUNCTIONAL HEARING GROUPS UNDER THE REVISED NMFS MARINE MAMMAL THRESHOLDS AND A REPRESENTATIVE OF EACH OF THE CURRENT FERRY CLASSES. THE RESULTS OF THIS ANALYSIS WILL FEED INTO STEP 2.  FERRY VESSEL DESIGN.  THE IMO UNDERWATER NOISE SHIPPING GUIDELINES (IMO 2014) IDENTIFY THE DESIGN PHASE AS THE MOST COST-EFFECTIVE OPPORTUNITY TO REDUCE VESSEL UNDERWATER NOISE.  WSF HAS SKILLED VESSEL DESIGNERS AND A NAVAL ARCHITECT WITH EXPERTISE IN PROPELLER DESIGN, TO ASSIST WITH THIS ISSUE. AS WSF MOVES FORWARD WITH THE 5-PROPELLER PROPOSALS THE UNDERWATER NOISE RESULTS SHOULD BE INCORPORATED INTO WSF DESIGN CRITERIA.
